title: Seventh
description: Photograph caption dated August 22, 1964 reads, "Ruby Reid, 38252 N. 102nd St. Palmdale, selects her prize of bowling ball, bag and shoes from Henry Levant of Reseda Bowl." The Valley Times sponsored contest started on Flag Day, June 14, 1964, at the corner of Parthenia Street and Van Nuys Boulevard, Panorama City, in a Hughes Market parking lot. Robert LeMaire ascended forty feet up a flagpole to a specially built platform where he remained for 36 days before climbing back down on July 20, 1964. Prizes were given out to those who could guess the exact number of days LeMaire would stay at the top of the flagpole. The top prize was a $1,000 check

description: Portland, Ore. — In the 1965 WIBC Championship Tournament, bowlers may wear dresses, blouses and skirts or culottes. No slacks will be permitted. Special attention is called to this rule so that no bowler will be embarrassed by appearing at the tournament in improper apparel.

title: Local Keglerette Is First Nisei To Join WIBC-No Objections
description: Another Nisei in the Mile High City has taken the initiative to recieve national recognition in furthering our achievements in the field of sports. Rosa Mayeda, wife of Dr. Takashi Mayeda of 2545 Champa St., recently became a member of the Woman's International Bowling Congress, Inc. She is believed to be the first Nisei in the Rocky Mountain region and perhaps in the nation to be accepted in the national organization as a full-fledged member. The WIBC has a membership similar to the American Bowling Congress for men which has a strong “White Only” restriction. The Nisei placed her application through Sylvia Bem, secretary of the Denver WIBC office last month. Meanwhile, during the period when her membership was sent to national headquarters, it was expected that there would be some objection. Never-the-less, she received her offici-ally-sealed card without any statement regarding exclusion of non-Whites. The local office secretary is very sympathetic with Nisei and । wanted to see more Nisei become members in order to secure equality in bowling. Mrs. Mayeda bowled in a citysanctioned league recently and I made an excellent showing among the Hakujin wcwnen, it was learned. She is one of Denver most accurate and highest keglerette. As far as the Denver office is concerned, it was reported that that they will not discriminate members on account of racial backgrounds.
subject: WIBC;Bowling associations;Segregation;Asian-American women
source: Kakushu Jji = Colorado Times (Denver, CO.), 15 March 1950. Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection. Colorado State Library.
image_alt_text: black and white scan of newspaper clipping for "Local Keglerette Is First Nisei To Join WIBC-No Objections" article

title: WIBC Removes Racial Clause
description: ST. PAUL, June 5 — The Women's International Bowling Congress, following the lead of the American Bowling Congress, today removed the controversial racial clause from its by-laws. Mrs. Jeannette Knepprath of Milwaukee, WIBC president, announced at the group's meeting here that the 70 delegates present had unanimously voted to drop the “whites only" requirement.
subject: WIBC;Bowling associations;Segregation
source: Kakushu Jji = Colorado Times (Denver, CO.), 6 June 1950. Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection. Colorado State Library
image_alt_text: black and white scan of newspaper clipping for "WIBC Removes Racial Clause" article

title: Color Line' Now Is Before WIBC
description: MILWAUKEE, May 15. — (AP) —Twelve Negro couples were refused permission to bowl last night in a “husband and wife” competition held under the regulations of the Women’s International Bowling Congress. Mrs. Elsa Schalla, an employe of the Milwaukee Women’s Bowling Assn. present at the alleys, said that the Negro couples were barred under the WIBC rule which limits membership to “white females.” Isaaih W. Pyant, one of the Negroes barred, said the group had reserveld an entire shift “so that no one would be embarrassed bowling with us.” The Negroes refused return of their entry money, saying they wanted to bowl. They called James Dorsey, prominent Negro attorney, who discussed the matter with alley proprietors and said later he would consult the district attorney’s office, The tournament is sponsored by the Milwaukee Sentinel. The WIBC is not affiliated with the American Bowling Congress, the men’s organization which last week struck its “white males” clause from the constitution in the face of numerous lawsuits,
subject: WIBC;Bowling associations;African-American women;Segregation
source: The Rocky Mountain News (Denver, CO.), 16 May 1950. Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection. Colorado State Library.
